text:
So super late but on the off chance someone wants more info on the sleep problems:

I've personally experienced most types of them and regularly get startled by insects that don't exist when I'm waking up. They're not lucid dreams, they happen outside of REM sleep while you're falling asleep or waking up.

For hallucinations the brain starts switching over to dream mode without shutting down real senses first. For sleep paralysis the brain shuts down motor control too early, typically while also inducing a hallucination too early.

They're really just an annoyance for most people. I cope by not believing what I see for a couple minutes when I wake up, and honestly the huge imaginary spiders I sometimes wake up to are kind of amusing in a way.

Anyway Sharky was fine, there's not really a trigger for these things. I hope this comment helps someone who's also been dealing with these problems!

text:
I've tried sleep paralysis once, as a small child.
I was having a nightmare about me getting eaten by a vacuum cleaner, and I kept on screaming for my mother in the dream, except every time i screamed, it would only be a whisper, and I couldn't move because of the vacuum cleaner. I then woke up, but I still couldn't move or call for my mother properly.
Honestly, thinking back, I'm amazed I didn't wet the bed out of sheer fright - I've never been so terrified since, and I actually haven't had any lucid dreams since.
I have, however, had dreams that I had full control of - those are f*cking amazing. weirdly enough, I only seem to have control in nightmares - like the time I dreamt of being the main character of the Half Life games, running through hordes of zombies, only to be attacked by my zombified mother after a narrow escape... DO I HAVE MOMMY ISSUES?!?

text:
For anyone wondering, sleep paralysis is essentially your body is asleep but your mind is awake. 
(You might not want to try this if you have heart or breathing problems as you might die) 
You can actually put yourself into a state of sleep paralysis as a way to try and induce a lucid dream, all you have to do is lay flat on your back as comfortable as you can and wait. 
The key is not to move, at all, you have to resist every little twitch which is difficult to do, the best way i've found is to keep repeating 'Don't Move' in your head. The twitches are just your brain sending signals to your body to see if its awake. 
After about 10-15 minutes you'll start to feel your fingers and toes going numb, you'll feel it slowly make it's way up your arms and legs until it eventually makes it's way to your torso. 
Your face will also go numb but i can't remember when it usually happens, think it's around the upper arm. 
Any twitch will reset the progress of the numbness hence having to resist. 
When your torso goes numb it'll feel like someone is sat on your chest which is when you know that you're almost complete. 
Soon after complete numbness has been achieved you'll be dreaming, now whether it'll be lucid or not i dunno. It's the only way i've been able to lucid dream and it only worked once, mostly i just use the method to fall asleep easier.
But i've never woken up with sleep paralysis.

text:
2:06:00 I used to get sleep paralysis with auditory hallucinations due to a combination of medications and insomnia. It can be a disconcerting experience but generally it's nothing to worry about.

When you sleep your brain shuts down motor function to prevent you from flailing about while unconscious. Paralysis occurs when your brain wakes up in the wrong order and cognitive function returns before motor function.
When you feel like you're being held down or that something is sitting on you it's because your brain "expects" to be able to move. It tries to solve the "not being able to move" problem by firing up your imagination and thinking up reasons as to why you can't move, and this is when you begin to hallucinate.

text:
Gura, a brief explanation of the Raid system which I hope is useful to you... those enemies that carry crossbows are called Pillagers, and they travel in groups. The leader of the group carries an Ominous Banner. When you kill the leader, you get a debuff called Bad Omen. If you should step into a village with the Bad Omen debuff active, it will start a raid, which will cause lots of Pillagers to appear and attack the village. The idea is that the player has to defend the village from the raid, and if they manage to do it, they get lots of prizes.

I would advise AGAINST activating the raid equipped as you are now, because honestly, you're not prepared for it. You - and the village you enter - will most likely be wiped out. Wait until you have more combat experience and/or the other HoloEN girls around to help you. Not to say it's not worth doing, but get some better equipment and more combat experience first. The people in chat telling you to enter a village were trolling you.

To get rid of the Bad Omen debuff, you can drink milk - milk can be acquired by right-clicking on a cow with a bucket in your hand. Alternatively, it will go away on its own after about an hour.

text: I have had sleep paralysis maybe 3 or 4 times, and it is honestly the closest I have ever felt to death. Seriously scary stuff. I never saw any hallucinations, but the most recent time I heard a scratching sound as if something with lots of sharp claws was scurrying around the carpet. It started from the door and slowly got closer to my bed until it was right next to me. It was very loud and I was sure that it was trying to kill me. But I couldnt move. I couldnt turn to look at it. I couldnt scream, or make any other noises. By what felt like my sheer will to survive I managed to wake up and sit straight up in my bed. Once I was awake I knew that it was just paralysis because I had had it before, but man that was the freakiest thing. All the other times I forget about what happened almost immediately after waking up just like a normal dream, but that one I will remember for a long time.

text:
Sleep Paralysis are so interesting. 

I experience them often. Usually when I am very tired, but don't just fall asleep right as I put my head on the pillow. 
What Gura described was a sleep paralysis. seeing shadows, and feeling weird things is common in sleep paralysis. Tho I've never experienced them. I usually don't "think" about opening my eyes during an episode. I just feel one is comming, its there, the feeling I get is that my head is about to burst, so I usually try get out of it as fast as possible. Tho sometimes I have found myself beeing in one for a long time. and with that feeling I get in the head in a paralysis, turns me into a trance state, that when I get out of it, I just feel my head is all mush. Can't really describe it better haha.

Tho Gura seem to have worse experience then I ever had with hallucination and stuff, aswell as trouble breathing, for me It does feel I can't breath, but I am pretty sure I am still breathing

text:
Oh man, the Sleep paralysis storytime really brought back memories... Mostly happened when i was a kid but recently came back again (as in 1 or 2 years ago).
Multiple times i had trouble breathing during sleep paralysis, usually either due to something on my chest or i happened to move my head to a certain angle.Pretty terrifying and uncomfortable so i can definitely relate to Gura's story. Though far more common for me was loud screaming, sometimes with the addition of silhouettes.

The most recent case i had was slightly more tamer (just paralysis) but it did happen 3 times in a row, I was trying to nap so after recovering from the sleep paralysis i went back to sleeping only for it happen again. After the 3rd experience i gave up, thankfully it was midday.

I am Gawr Gura, and I'm here to ask you a question.

Is a man not entitled to the sweat of his brow?
'No!' says the man in Washington, 'It belongs to the poor.'
'No!' says the man in the Vatican, 'It belongs to God.'
'No!' says the man in Moscow, 'It belongs to everyone.'

I rejected those answers; instead, I chose something different.
I chose the impossible. I chose...the city of Atlantis.
A city where the artist would not fear the censor.
Where the scientist would not be bound by petty morality.
Where the great would not be constrained by the small!

And with the sweat of your brow, Atlantis can become your city as well.

text: I had some sort of a sleep paralysis happen to me a few times. I'll wake up and know I'm awake but when I try to move it's like my body is made of lead and sapped of energy. Kinda like when your leg falls asleep and is hard to move i guess is the best similar feeling I can think of rn. I couldn't control my breathing but I could tell I was lightly breathing and luckily didn't feel suffocated. Also been shocked by an outlet and had a similar paralyzing feeling of becoming too drained, weak and heavy to move. Also have had Exploding Head Syndrome. I was going to bed one night like any other and when my body made the switch from conscious to sleeping I heard the loudest audio hallucination ever. It sounded like an inception noise or if you've ever heard sky trumpets. Imagine sticking your head into a tuba and being blasted x10. I shot up like YO WTF WAS THAT. I got up and asked if anyone else heard it because I legit thought that it was sky trumpets but alas nobody heard anything.

text: I've had many episodes of sleep paralysis, but by far the worse i had was one were i felt my whole body almost paralyzed so i felt like i could just roll out of bed, the thing is, it was kinda like... multiple layers of dreams where i would crawl out of bed, try to reach the door of my room  just to realize that i was still paralized in my bed.. and happened over and over again.... about 15-20 times in a row... and every time the dreams were longer and longer... i woke up feeling extremely tired but afraid to go back to sleep

author: @willy8103

text:
¬†@marlonyo¬†  your brain releases a hallucinogen called DMT during the last stage of a sleep cycle (a person has usually 3-5 cycles each having 4 stages). That is what causes dreams‚Äîor nightmares.
Sleep paralysis is exactly when you‚Äôre at the REM stage (dream-causing stage) while also at the same time being in an earlier light-sleeping/waking stage, which causes parts of you to be awake while you‚Äôre body‚Äôs muscles are super relaxed (so you don‚Äôt act out your dreams) and parts of your brain are still asleep causing the ‚Äúwaking‚Äù hallucinations (you‚Äôre not really fully awake, you‚Äôre just having what is similar to lucid dreaming, but terrifying)

It‚Äôs like having a really bad drug trip on top of being paralyzed. Although the best way to resolve that is to wiggle your toes and fingers and assure yourself that you‚Äôll be fine, because fear and panic is what makes it nightmarish rather than dreamlike.
author: @DrPonner

text:
I had alot of nightmares during my childhood, so i developed an ability to force myself to wake up from any unwanted dream at anytime.

During sleep paralysis, i cant do that, so i panicked alot during my first time and it last for quite a while..... Lucky for me it wasnt terrifying as others put it.

Being calm and having happy thoughts during a sleep paralysis were the best solutions for me. The more you struggle, the more tired you will feel, and you cant going back to sleep for a while.
author: @MenrvaS

text: For those who had sleep paralysis try this tips. Good sleep hygiene by making a good sleep habit like sleep 6 hours minimal at the same schedule every day, ensuring a comfortable sleep environment and avoiding caffeine intake or distraction. Try to sleep on your side rather than on your back. Also try stress management. If the symptoms is persist, you should consider go to a doctor for a consultation or prescribe you a medication. Worst cases it usually correlated to other sleep disorder such as narcolepsy or sleep apnoea, mental health disorder, medication side effect, or substance abuse.

text:
Sleep paralysis is interesting, i actually want to explore more in it. I did see spectres n something moving in my vision. It was scary but im more intrigued where my mind leads me. So i tried to move my fingers and it worked. I got up from bed and it was hard. Yes im still in sp, but thats all i could do atm. Kinda wished i can walk out to living room. I can breathe already compared to first few sp where im unfamiliar of a state where im in. Now im wishing if i encounter it again, ill get out from my room and walk in the state. Oh, one thing, youll never can speak in that state but u can hear it in ur head. I was terrified at first but eventually im used to it. I currently at a stage where i can move my head and look around me, yes shadows behind the curtains are scary af but its in ur head. Im also at a point where i can lift up my body by pushing up with arms but to no avail, I couldn't yet. 

In conclusion, as creepy as sp gives you, its an interesting experience you can have because its like ur in another dimension except its not real. Next time you get it, try explore what can you do in that state.
